  "answer": "The critic misreads the forbidden case. The target’s mechanism posits that depletion of *easily accessible, fuel-rich* ores and deforestation-driven ecological damage undermined the economic basis of the palace system, triggering collapse. The forbidden case states that copper production peaked in the 12th century BC and forests remained extensive. These observations are not contradictory: a peak in gross output can be achieved through intensified, less efficient deep mining and massive fuel consumption precisely when the system is under terminal stress—the peak is the last gasp, not a sign of health. Extensive forests can still be present yet insufficient to sustain both escalated smelting demands and agricultural stability without severe erosion, exactly as the mechanism describes. The forbidden case does not specify that the *easily accessible* ores were still abundant or that the ecological cascade (soil erosion, agricultural decline) did not occur; it therefore does not falsify the mechanism’s core causal sequence. The mechanism remains grounded in actual events because it predicts a production spike driven by desperate intensification immediately before collapse, which is consistent with the 12th-century peak."
